    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:bf810cec-9c6a-423c-9cdf-bf8639b3ef7d",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 13-year-old girl who walks into the clinic with her mother, her eyes slightly downcast and her arms crossed tightly over her chest. She is of average build for her age, dressed neatly in a hoodie and jeans, and speaks softly, often glancing at her mother for reassurance before answering questions. She attends 8th grade at a local middle school, where she is described by her teachers as bright but overly cautious and perfectionistic. She has a small, tight-knit group of friends, though she frequently worries about what they think of her.\n\n{patientName} has been experiencing persistent, uncontrollable worry for the past eight months about a wide range of topics — school performance, her parents' health, natural disasters, and her own future. She reports daily muscle tension, frequent headaches, and difficulty falling asleep because her \"brain won't stop thinking.\" On particularly bad days, she notices her heart racing and her palms sweating during classes, especially before exams or oral presentations.\n\nAt home, {patientName} enjoys drawing anime-style characters, reading fantasy novels, and watching nature documentaries with her father. She has recently started avoiding her weekly dance class because the thought of performing in front of peers triggers intense anticipatory anxiety. Her appetite has been slightly reduced, and her mother reports noticing irritability and tearfulness in the evenings that are unusual for her daughter.\n\n{patientName} lives with her mother, father, and 10-year-old brother in a suburban home. Her parents are both working professionals and describe the family environment as supportive but busy. Despite their best efforts to reassure her, {patientName}'s worries have not improved and have begun to affect her school attendance, with two absences in the last month attributed to somatic complaints like stomachaches and headaches on the mornings of major tests."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:37270d28-6d88-4b20-9d8e-6ba37316ff41",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no prior psychiatric hospitalizations. She was seen by her pediatrician approximately one year ago for recurrent stomachaches and headaches, which were evaluated and found to have no organic cause. At that time, anxiety was mentioned but not formally diagnosed. She has a history of mild separation anxiety in early childhood (ages 5–7) that resolved without intervention.\n\n{patientName} has no significant chronic medical conditions. She had a course of amoxicillin for streptococcal pharyngitis at age 11 and developed a mild urticarial rash, which is now documented as a drug allergy. Her immunizations are up to date. She does not smoke, drink alcohol, or use recreational substances. She denies any history of trauma, abuse, or significant losses. Her academic performance has historically been above average, though recently she has been struggling to complete homework due to perfectionism and excessive self-doubt. There is a notable maternal family history of anxiety disorder and paternal history of depression, both relevant risk factors for GAD."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
